ect." But this isn't always the case. A story like this won't always correspond to a low-key or high-key image. It can also perfectly represent an overexposed or underexposed image, which have nothing to do with high-key or low-key. Keep that in mind. Okay, so what characteristics will we find in both high-key and low-key photography? As we've already seen in high-key photography, low-key photography is characterized by the dominance of bright colors and highlights in the scene. In contrast, low-key photography is characterized by the opposite: dark colors predominate in the shadows. Generally speaking, high-key photography features low contrast due to the use of ambient light, as the goal is to avoid creating too many or dark shadows. In contrast, low-key photography does produce shadows because it uses a focused light source. The aim is to illuminate the scene by focusing on the point of interest. Continuing with lighting, high-key photography may require more than one light source. If using natural light, the choice of location, how to control and reflect the light, and the selection of the elements— in my case, a portrait—will play a crucial role. In low-key photography, the key elements are the colors, the person, and the background. Most likely, we wo n't use a lot of light sources; one light source will be enough to achieve our image. Now, to understand a little about where the concepts of high-key and low-key photography come from, I'm going to refer to the Zone System created by Ansel Adams. He was a photographer who organized a system of 11 zones—at least that's how I know it. Actually, there are 10 zones plus Zone Zero, which is absolute black, but there are 11 zones. This 11-zone system shows, in a simplified way, the grayscale, the tonal scale that we will find within a photograph. To make this easier to analyze, it's very useful to look at the photos in black and white; that's where we will be able to appreciate the shades of gray in the photos. In 'Zone Zero,' we will find absolute black, black with no information, and in Zone 10, which would be Zone 11, pure white, also with no information. Between these two is the entire grayscale, which simplifies the grayscale we find in our images. So, in this way, we will find photos that... They adapt to the long-zone designation, meaning the photo has a large amount of grayscale in its composition. On the other hand, we also find photos that we can categorize as short-zone, which aren't necessarily light and dark. We also have short-zone photos that represent very low- contrast photos where, for example, mid-gray tones may predominate. We won't have a large number of very pronounced shadows or very marked highlights. But also within short-zone, we will find high-key and low-key photographs. Now, I think it's important to mention some points, some tips that are very important when trying to achieve either of these two styles. I think what this will do is allow us to visualize a photo and be able to create it. That's what interests me most. I have an idea; having the resources to be able to do it is the most important thing, and when I talk about resources, I'm talking about knowing how to carry it out, not other types of resources. The first piece of advice, perhaps already obvious at this point, is to shoot in RAW format because when we are working to achieve a high-key image...  In low-key photography, we're always going to be pushing the boundaries of what's possible. Remember, the goal is always to expose correctly, so our histogram and our photograph will always be on the verge of losing some information in the highlights or shadows. So, beyond correct exposure, what we want is for our image to have the best possible dynamic range, and that's what the red format, not the JPG, will give us. Another important point is selecting the right elements. When I say the right elements, I mean the elements of color or tone. For example, if I want to take a low-key photograph of this product, I'll try to set the scene, using the darkest possible background, all within the low-key tones. If, for example, I include a lot of white elements, it will be much more difficult to achieve the desired low-key result. Even if it's well-exposed and very beautiful, I won't be able to classify it as a low-key photograph. Another very important point is correct exposure. I've mentioned it quite a bit in this video, but it's true: when you're going to take this type of photograph, you shouldn't... Overexposing a photo, for example, by thinking that being overexposed will make it a high-key photograph, is a common mistake. A very important point, as with everything in photography, is being able to control and master the light according to what we want to create. For example, if we want a high-key photograph, it's best to use a soft light source that is as comprehensive as possible and has good luminous capacity. We might even need to use more than one light source. If we want to create a low- key photograph, we'll be looking to illuminate only the subject, perhaps with backlighting or side lighting, so that the background doesn't receive enough light and the elements appear dark. A high-key or low-key photograph doesn't necessarily require backgrounds without detail; that's another recurring error. It's a common misconception that if a photograph is low-key, the background has to be completely black and lack detail. Similarly, in high-key, backgrounds don't necessarily have to be bright white. Now, let's get down to business and put everything I've said into practice. We'll take some photos on set.  In this case, I'm going to do product photography, specifically food photography. My subject is churros, and what I initially want is to achieve some high-key and some low-key photos with the same element. The first thing I did was divide all the elements I have into two groups, which I think could be useful— both light and dark elements that I'll eventually use for each of the setups. I did the same with the backgrounds and bases I have for the high-key photography. What I'm going to put together is a set with the appropriate elements, and what I want to create is abundant and enveloping lighting where I find soft shadows that aren't too deep. I don't want to create a very high-contrast image from the lighting alone, but it will have its own contrast due to the different elements and the different textures and colors that each of the elements I'm going to use to set up the scene may have. I'll be using an 80x1 meter softworks light as the main light, which will give me this soft light to lift the shadows. I have two options: on the one hand, I can add another light to lift these shadows, but I have to have a lot of it, given that  This secondary light doesn't end up creating a shadow in the opposite direction of the main light, so in these cases it's very useful to use a bounce instead of a light because with the bounce, whether it's the 5-in-1 on its silver side or its white side, it will never create a shadow in the other direction. The bounce will always be filling in and compensating for that shadow, but it won't create a shadow in the opposite direction. In that respect, we can be very confident. [Music] Okay, and here we see the result of these photos we just took. [Music] For the low-key photography I want to achieve, I'm going to use as a background, initially, I want to test what happens with the gray background I have here behind me. I'm going to set up the set far enough from the background so that practically no light reaches it, so it will be quite overexposed, and I reckon it will end up almost black. On the other hand, for lighting, I'm going to use the strip box with its grid so that the light is as closed as possible and illuminates only the product and not much more. From there, I'll see if I need to shield it. Just enough to narrow the beam of light a little more, but my idea is for the light to focus on the product and leave the rest practically in shadow. Now let's see how the photos turned out in high key. [Music] Ah, good. And beyond the technical aspects we consider in each of these two photography styles, one of the most important points to keep in mind when doing this is the message we want to convey, the feeling our photo will transmit. For example, high-key photographs are often used to convey serenity, purity, or joy. On the other hand, and I don't want to say the complete opposite because the reality is that it's not like that, low-key photographs will convey a feeling of intimacy, elegance, or intensity. For example, if I have to photograph healthy, light, homemade food, I might use high-key photographs with bright colors and soft shadows because the message is much more coherent with that than if I use a low-key photograph. And, for example, if I want to photograph a hearty, filling, and very tasty hamburger, I might end up using low-key photography with dark colors. The burger really stands out with a side light that 's more consistent with the message I want to convey. And that's all for today's video. Thank you so much for watching until the end. I hope this video was helpful, not too long, and above all, that you liked the photos and the lighting setups. I'm actually quite happy with them. I can never quite decide whether to use high-key or low-key lighting; I really like both. If there's one you like more, leave a comment—it might help me decide sometime. And now, if I have nothing else to add, subscribe to the channel if you haven't already. Ask questions, leave comments, and I'll see you in the next video. [Applause]

